:"","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/tcvtwo/writing_world_s_most_boring_quine","submitter_user":{"username":"rtpg","created_at":"2016-07-06T05:00:24.000-05:00","is_admin":false,"about":"","is_moderator":false,"karma":2934,"avatar_url":"/avatars/rtpg-100.png","invited_by_user":"BruceM"},"tags":["programming"]},{"short_id":"imtxa9","short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/imtxa9","created_at":"2023-03-02T07:50:27.000-06:00","title":"How We Scan Container Images for Vulnerabilities at Mergify","url":"https://blog.mergify.com/how-we-scan-container-images-for-vulnerabilities-at-mergify/","score":2,"flags":1,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/imtxa9/how_we_scan_container_images_for","submitter_user":{"username":"jd","created_at":"2018-07-27T09:28:01.000-05:00","is_admin":false,"about":"CEO at Mergify","is_moderator":false,"karma":60,"avatar_url":"/avatars/jd-100.png","invited_by_user":"dege","github_username":"jd","twitter_username":"juldanjou"},"tags":["security"]},{"short_id":"s1efu8","short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/s1efu8","created_at":"2023-03-02T06:51:04.000-06:00","title":"How to model one-to-one relationships - Tigris Data Modeling Series","url":"https://www.tigrisdata.com/blog/modelling-one-to-one-relations/","score":-1,"flags":2,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/s1efu8/how_model_one_one_relationships_tigris","submitter_user":{"username":"garrensmith","created_at":"2020-02-11T11:08:46.000-06:00","is_admin":false,"about":"Prisma Engineer, CouchDB PMC. Rust, Databases and distributed systems. Lives in sunny South Africa.","is_moderator":false,"karma":104,"avatar_url":"/avatars/garrensmith-100.png","invited_by_user":"banjiewen","github_username":"garrensmith"},"tags":["databases"]},{"short_id":"vhp170","short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/vhp170","created_at":"2023-03-02T05:49:57.000-06:00","title":"OpenPGP / GnuPG notepad recommendations?","url":"","score":8,"flags":0,"comment_count":15,"description":"\u003cp\u003eCan the community recommend some trusted, secure, open-source, easy-to-use notepad-like editors that can encrypt / decrypt the text with GnuPG out of the box?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eFor my own use-cases I have my own scripts that tie \u003ccode\u003egpg\u003c/code\u003e with my favorite editor, but I‚Äôm looking for a simple to use editor (like LeafPad, MousePad, Howl, etc.) that given a file-path (which is either an \u003ccode\u003e.gpg\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e.asc\u003c/code\u003e file) will transparently decrypt it, allow the user to view / edit it, and upon closing to just re-encrypt that file keeping the recipients intact (and perhaps signing it).  (It doesn‚Äôt matter if its for the terminal or X.)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI‚Äôve found many password managers that rely on GnuPG, and I bet there are plugins for the various \u003ccode\u003evi\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eemacs\u003c/code\u003e clones out there, but so far nothing sensible on this other front‚Ä¶\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003chr\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eP.S.  I‚Äôm starting to suspect that the whole OpenPGP ecosystem was built with only one use-case in mind:  encrypted and/or signed email.  The rest, although technically possible, suffers from a complete lack of actually usable tools‚Ä¶\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eP.P.S:  No, \u003ccode\u003eage\u003c/code\u003e doesn‚Äôt solve this problem either.  It just replaces one set of cryptographic primitives with another, but on the usability front I would say it‚Äôs even a bit worse than GnuPG for normal people‚Ä¶\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"Can the community recommend some trusted, secure, open-source, easy-to-use notepad-like editors that can encrypt / decrypt the text with GnuPG out of the box?\r\n\r\nFor my own use-cases I have my own scripts that tie `gpg` with my favorite editor, but I'm looking for a simple to use editor (like LeafPad, MousePad, Howl, etc.) that given a file-path (which is either an `.gpg` or `.asc` file) will transparently decrypt it, allow the user to view / edit it, and upon closing to just re-encrypt that file keeping the recipients intact (and perhaps signing it).  (It doesn't matter if its for the terminal or X.)\r\n\r\nI've found many password managers that rely on GnuPG, and I bet there are plugins for the various `vi` and `emacs` clones out there, but so far nothing sensible on this other front...\r\n\r\n----\r\n\r\nP.S.  I'm starting to suspect that the whole OpenPGP ecosystem was built with only one use-case in mind:  encrypted and/or signed email.  The rest, although technically possible, suffers from a complete lack of actually usable tools...\r\n\r\nP.P.S:  No, `age` doesn't solve this problem either.  It just replaces one set of cryptographic primitives with another, but on the usability front I would say it's even a bit worse than GnuPG for normal people...","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/vhp170/openpgp_gnupg_notepad_recommendations","submitter_user":{"username":"ciprian_craciun","created_at":"2022-02-14T13:47:43.000-06:00","is_admin":false,"about":"IT enthusiast, from programming to operating systems, from networking to cryptography, from cloud to hardware, from Erlang to Java.","is_moderator":false,"karma":813,"avatar_url":"/avatars/ciprian_craciun-100.png","invited_by_user":"syn-ack"},"tags":["ask","cryptography"]},{"short_id":"ubsusz","short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/ubsusz","created_at":"2023-03-02T01:35:37.000-06:00","title":"new pijul beta release","url":"https://crates.io/crates/pijul/1.0.0-beta.4","score":36,"flags":0,"comment_count":6,"description":"","description_plain":"","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/ubsusz/new_pijul_beta_release","submitter_user":{"username":"tankf33der","created_at":"2017-06-07T13:06:59.000-05:00","is_admin":false,"about":"","is_moderator":false,"karma":456,"avatar_url":"/avatars/tankf33der-100.png","invited_by_user":"james"},"tags":["relea